	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Late Afternoon posts from Abashi</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=146766" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/045298.html">Iksar Monk Shackle of Rock -- Faction screwup? Abashi, please take a look.</a><P>

The Ogres are KoS since the Timorous Deep itemization and are apparently Venril Sathir Faction.<P>

<B>Thanks for the heads-up. Oogwamp should be off of that faction in the next patch. I would continue, however, to be wary of his compatriots.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047526.html">Gordon, Rallos should go coin only...just look at how many posts are pro coin</a><P>

Recently, iv gone through all of the posts dealing with the coin only issue on Rallos Zek. Almost every single one is pro coin only loot, and, they all have people practically begging on their knees to do so with sometimes in the hundreds of replies agreeing that it should go coin only. The replies asking for it to stay the same are, in all honestly, few and far between.<P>

<B>I've heard the request... I've also heard a fair number of requests that it be left as-is. In any case, as I mentioned in a thread earlier this week, any further decisions in this regard are on hold until we implement the VZ/TZ moves. I should have an ETA for this hopefully Monday.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<Hr align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047628.html">Why not just fix the hybrid penalty?</a><P>

Why not just fix the hybrid penalty? <P>

<B>To answer your posed question as clearly as possible: Because it's not broken.</B><P>

Verant has already agreed with the idea that hybrids do not need an experience penalty since they have been balanced with the classes that don't have a penalty.<P>

<B>No we haven't. The additional experience required for certain races and classes (I hate calling it a penalty since it isn't very accurate) is purposeful and appropriate.</B><P>

They also say they can't remove the penalty because hybrids would suddenly gain several levels.<P>

<B>This statement was made in regards to experience requirements in general, whether higher or lower than average. Experience tables are not subject to adjustment post-release due to the effect that they have on the game.<P> 

Though there may be a couple of cases where we should have applied additional experience requirements for certain race/class combos, the existing cases where more experience is required than average are sufficient and appropriate.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<Hr align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047750.html">A respectful question for Gordon</a><P>

At level 48, if I died without being ressed, I could get all of the experience back in a couple of hours. I think you will agree that the exp loss for level 48's is appropriate and sufficient to give them a sense of excitement from dangerous areas. <P>

If level 48 players can still enjoy EQ and still experience excitement and a sense of danger, with that amount of experience loss, why do you think that a level 53 player needs to lose 10 hours' worth of experience to feel that same sense of danger? <P>

If two hours worth is good enough for 48, why isn't it good enough for 52 and beyond? <P>

<B>With the increase in power that comes from gaining levels post-50, so does the increase in the risk of losing that power. Back in the low 20s, it would only take about 30 minutes to recover the experience lost in death. The issue is basically the same here.<P>
 
As I've mentioned in several threads over the past couple of days, players remain in continual control of how much risk they subject their characters to. If the risk of dying without a resurrect is too high, my suggestion would be to avoid situations that increase the potential to realize the risk, or form relationships which will help mitigate the risk should it be realized.<P>

Though many have made different arguments as to why they feel that the experience loss is excessive, it's still something that the players can control. We're firm on the experience-loss issue.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="Center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047816.html">Death by poor coding</a><P>

Okay I am sick to death of seeing this issue skirted...I zone into a place and drop for 10000 damage or go under water and rather than having full bar of air i just die....situations like this are result of coding and not high risk areas and the like.<P>

<B>Just a note, we think that we found the situation that was causing this to happen. We'll be putting it up live the next time that we patch. Since it happens so infrequently and we don't have any way to reproduce it 100% of the time, we won't know for sure until it is live.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047822.html">NECROMANCERS NEED A TRAVELING SPELL</a><P>

My goodness. I spend 75% of my time traveling. Even if it is only 25% of sow. Or teleport home only using all your mana. Man I would have more fun playing. I love to travel to new places but If you need food or sell items and you are KOS everywhere. ACK!!!!<P>

<B>As someone who plays a necromancer, I can answer virtually any post about them from the standpoint of personal experience.<P> 

Necromancers can do virtually everything under the Sun. A traveling spell wouldn't be appropriate.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047823.html">ABASHI --- What is Verant's Official Stance on EQ Addiction, Excessive Playtime, etc?</a><P>

Does Verant employ any professional consultants from any area like Psychology, Sociology, Psychiarty, etc to offer opinions on the matter?<P>

<B>Not specifically for that purpose. One of our game designers does have a degree in psychology, and most of our people have degrees, of which psychology and sociology classes are often included in the curriculum, but we don't purposely design for addiction, we design for excitement and fun, which are characteristics that some find addicting.</B><P>

Does Verant plan to limit play time in any way, shape or form?<P>

<B>No. We provide a persistent world where one can feel free to come and go as they please. It is in the end the responsibility of each player, whether an adult themselves, or whether the account was purchased by a responsible adult, to regulate their own playtime to what works for them.</B><P>

Does Verant reccommend a certain play time limit for its players? Does Verant believe that there is such a thing as excessive play time?<P>

<B>There is certainly such a thing as "excessive play time", but it's not a rigid value that we can set, but is more subjective in terms of each individual player. Certainly playtime becomes excessive when gameplay begins to interfere with responsibilities, every day life, and commitments to a job or family.</B><P>

Has Verant received any complaints from parents of children that play EverQuest, or from players themselves regarding playtime?<P>

<B>Not to my knowledge, of course it wouldn't make much sense for parents of minor players to hold us responsible for a service that they pay for with their credit card. <P>

Just like television, sports, and computer usage in general, parents are ultimately responsible for the content to which they allow their children access. Though there are companies that specialize, for instance, in selling parental control that limit TV viewing times for children, no one really holds the TV networks at fault for sending out the signal 24/7. <P>

In any case, any activity that provides some form of fun, excitement, or stimulation can be taken to an extreme. "Games" by their nature provide those factors. Though we are certainly proud of the success of EverQuest and amount that people play and enjoy the game, we certainly do not want to see people hurting their families, careers, or other relationships over it. <P>

Please play responsibly.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<A href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047845.html">Can the live team please look at this?</a><P>

Upon reaching level 54, I was able to buy Voltaic Draugh. My first impression is that it would've been a cold based spell (From reading other posts prior to the release of Kunark). When I scribed it, I noticed it had the magical DD symbol and when I casted it, sure enough, it looked like lightning.<P>

With this news I hoped Draught of Jiva would be our cold based version in this line. Its not one you can buy, so I wasn't able to purchase it when I first reached level 55. A few days ago my guild looted one from Sebilis and I was given the scroll. Turns out this is also a magical based spell.<P>

<B>They are both supposed to save vs. magic. Draught of Jiva has an additional effect associated with it. I'll give other readers here a chance to jump in and comment on it rather than releasing the info myself.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047848.html">Whoo hoo! Good news about damage dealing root spells.</a><P>

<B>Some of you will recall that we made some changes to the druid root series a month or so ago that was supposed to make them function better. Though there was a bit of a placebo effect at the time where many agreed that they were working better, after a while it turned out that there wasn't a real difference. <P>

The problem was that the damage being dealt by these spells would cause the spell itself to break. In the text window, the users of these spells would actually see the "wear off" message *before* the spell effect message. <P>

Anyway, this is now fixed (really… we mean it this time :). Damaged caused by a damage dealing root spell no longer have a chance to break the root. This includes the entire druid root series, as well as the necromancer undead-only "Hungry Earth" spell. The fix is live on test and should go to the production servers in the next patch.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047860.html">Are account trades Legal?</a><P>

Can I trade my account for someone else's account or is this illegal as well? I know selling your account is illegal, but is trading it?<P>

<B>Transfer of accounts between individuals is prohibited by the license agreement. This applies whether the account is transferred for cash, another account in kind, or any other form of consideration. <P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<A href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047863.html">Is The Kly Overseer supposed to cast this Abashi?</a><P>

I know you say you fixed the spell levels for mobs inside the Crypt of Dalnir. The goo used to have a 600point poison spell which was thankfully fixed. However, myself (52 wizard) and a friend (51 warrior) went to go get ourselves a nice necklace from Dalnir. Well we get to the room, clear all the other regular Sarnaks out and then pull "The Kly Overseer". This guy starts casting regular wizard spells, no biggy, he is green to me. All the sudden i am slashed by ice and dead. This happens after resisting most of his spells and still at full health because of manaskin.<P>

Now as a wizard i am pretty sure i have no spell in my inventory around levle 34-39 (which is what this mob is) that does near Ice comet damage. Just wondering if maybe this little Sarnak guy has come across a spell i seemed to have missed in my years of wizardly training or is it still a bugged mob sith an over powered spell.<P>

<B>There are cases where particular NPCs can be given access to a spell that is normally not part of their repertoire. I'm not sure what the deal is in this particular case, but I'll check into it.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047875.html">Necro rez spell is totaly useless</a><P>

I am very unhappy with this spell. as far as I can see there was no point in giving it to us. I cannot think of 1 person who is going to let me kill them when they lose exp just so I can rez someone else. This spell should have been 45+ mobs not other players. What was the point in having it if I will never be able to use it? would you let a necro sacrifice your higher level guy knowing that you are going to loose exp and not be able to get a rez?<P>

<B>There's a difference between "useless" and "costly". The spell definitely has use, but as it is a tremendous ability, it is very costly. I would agree that in many cases this spell isn't the best choice in how to proceed, but I can also think of several where it's certainly better than nothing.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<A href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047887.html">The big lie</a><P>

Something has been nagging me about the statements Verrant has made int he past about camping and it finally hit me. As best I can tell, the Verrant position is that camping was never intended, the "proper" activity would be to fight into a dungeon (maybe all the way to the bottom) then call it a day. If this is the intention, why do some of the important mobs have placeholders?<P>

<B>Placeholders are just another way to set up spawns and have their appearance tied to some random value. They also require that something be killed, avoiding a situation where someone just has to wait around long enough. <P>

There are situations where long spawns are appropriate, and other situations where placeholders with a percent chance of spawning a certain mob is appropriate. It just depends on the effect that the game designer is going for.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
